of course, anything that is written in kanji can be written both in hiragana and katakana, so it's not correct to assume that the three alphabets are &quot;seperate&quot; so to speak.<br>
<br>
Occasionally, (and becoming something of a trend lately) parents will name their children without picking kanji for their name, in which case their name is written completely in hiragana.  (I have a friend named Emi, for instance, who writes her name totally in hiragana, and doesn't have any corresponding kanji).<br>
<br>
While coraxus is correct insofar as kanji are often associated with &quot;meanings&quot;, they also have definite pronounciations (as mentioned above), and these pronounciations change depending on the situation in which they are used.  Most kanji have both a kunyomi (japanese reading) and an onyomi (chinese reading).  The former can be thought of as the 'main reading' for that character and is generally used when that character is standing alone (i.e. as a verb or something) while the latter is often used when the character is part of a kanji compound with other characters.  There are often many (sometimes as many as a dozen) alternate readings for a single character, which is one of the primary reasons why japanese is often a challenge for westerners to learn.<br>
<br>
Furthermore, kanji are often modified by using hiragana; for instance, to indicate the tense of a verb, etc.  As noted above, most japanese words are 'associated' with a kanji, but can of course, be written in both hiragana or katakana (which is the way children learn to read before they have memorized all the complex kanji).<br>
<br>
I wouldn't say that Chinese &quot;use&quot; kanji, in so far as kanji *are* chinese characters, borrowed thousands of years ago and modified over the ages.  While many characters are somewhat different, often readers of each language can garner general meanings from looking at text/signs/etc. of the other language.  <br>
<br>
Of course Chinese has many many more &quot;kanji&quot; than Japanese (though often each character has less pronounciations than its japanese counterpart).  Within Japanese, there are aproximately 2,200 jyoyou (&quot;daily use&quot;) kanji which are required for minimal fluency (i.e. can read a newspaper), and estimates at the total number of kanji in use within japanese range up to ~5,000, though you will never encounter even half of that unless you are in an extremely specialized field.  In order to pass the level 1 noryokushiken (proficiency exam) you should probably know all 2,200 jyoyou kanji and most of their associated readings. (this is a much more difficult task than it sounds since the kanji can subsequently be recombined (with much altered pronounciations) with each other... so you end up needing to know many many more combinations than just the 2,200 basic kanji)<br>
<br>
